47:51.102 --> 47:54.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
No surprise, perhaps, a sense of
unease and
anxiety.

47:54.939 --> 47:58.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIA LOCKS, Whitney Museum of
American Art:
It's been a tumultuous few
years.

47:58.642 --> 48:04.582 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For better or for worse, I think
a presidential
election can sometimes be a
moment when we,

48:04.615 --> 48:08.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as a country and as a kind of
society, do
ask ourselves pretty hard
questions about

48:09.019 --> 48:11.655 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how we understand ourselves
individually and
collectively.

48:11.689 --> 48:13.891 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, what did you
see artists
saying?

48:13.924 --> 48:15.693 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
CHRISTOPHER Y.

48:15.726 --> 48:16.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LEW, Whitney Museum of American
Art: They're
thinking about the world in
which they live

48:16.727 --> 48:18.896 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in, and that can be defined in
different ways.

48:18.929 --> 48:22.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they may be thinking about a
specific
neighborhood, or they're
thinking about the

48:22.767 --> 48:27.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
city, and that what they're
making is intended
to kind of speak back to
society.

48:27.071 --> 48:32.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For them, it's not just a kind
of precious
bubble just to kind of look at,
in and of

48:32.343 --> 48:34.111 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
itself.

48:34.145 --> 48:37.581 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In a photography
series shot
over a year-and-a-half, Oto
Gillen captures

48:37.615 --> 48:42.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some of the mood and changes
brought about
by income disparities in his
native New York

48:42.753 --> 48:44.388 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
City.

48:44.421 --> 48:46.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
OTO GILLEN, Artist: This kind of
sense of
anxiety that everyone is having
about the

48:46.824 --> 48:52.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
future, and the idea that the
future has arrived
faster than we thought it would,
and in a

48:52.696 --> 48:59.537 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
way that we didn't expect to, to
show a certain
state of America that may not be
visible to

48:59.570 --> 49:03.340 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
everyone, but not in a
necessarily definitive
way.

49:03.374 --> 49:09.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Like, I want it to be open and
for people
to just be able to look at the
world around

49:09.680 --> 49:11.549 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
them and ask questions.

49:11.582 --> 49:14.451 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Other works take
a more direct
approach.

49:14.485 --> 49:19.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Debtfair, by a group of artists
tied to the
Occupy movement, connects the
debt incurred

49:19.390 --> 49:25.262 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by college students to the
poverty many artists
face, while the vibrant
sculptures and stained

49:25.296 --> 49:31.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
glass windows by Raul de Nieves,
a young artist
making his first appearance in
the biennial,

49:31.402 --> 49:34.004 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
approach anxiety through
allegory.

49:34.038 --> 49:35.973 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What is that story that you're
trying to tell?

49:36.006 --> 49:37.808 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
RAUL DE NIEVES, Artist: The idea
of fear.

49:37.842 --> 49:40.811 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Like, how do we confront fear,
you know?

49:40.845 --> 49:47.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when you realize what fear
is, it's like
you should acknowledge it and
greet it by

49:47.184 --> 49:52.289 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the hand and walk away, so that
you overcome
this idea of fear.

49:52.323 --> 49:56.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in a sense, like, being a
part of such
a grandiose show is a form of
fear.

49:56.861 --> 49:59.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Fear for you, you
mean as an
artist?

49:59.430 --> 50:01.065 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RAUL DE NIEVES: Yes.

50:01.098 --> 50:07.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I'm not afraid to say that,
because it
was -- you're like, what is this
going to

50:07.071 --> 50:11.308 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
say, and how do I want to, like,
portray myself
and my work?

50:11.342 --> 50:13.711 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Other signs of
the times?

50:13.744 --> 50:20.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A video installation by a
collective called
Postcommodity shows several
miles of the U.S.-Mexico

50:20.351 --> 50:22.219 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
border fence.

50:22.253 --> 50:28.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some of the work here, like
Celeste Dupuy-Spencer's
drawing Trump Rally, is overtly
political.

50:28.726 --> 50:34.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Frances Stark's Censorship Now
is a different
kind of provocation, arguing
that censorship,

50:34.632 --> 50:39.203 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and not free expression, would
empower artists
by raising their profile.

50:39.236 --> 50:44.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, overall, this biennial, as
opposed to
some in the past, takes a less
aggressive

50:44.942 --> 50:45.910 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
stance.

50:45.943 --> 50:47.645 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Whitney director Adam Weinberg:

50:47.678 --> 50:49.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADAM WEINBERG, Director, Whitney
Museum of
American Art: I do see political
work, but

50:49.546 --> 50:50.948 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I do not think it's hectoring.

50:50.981 --> 50:52.883 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I don't think it's
finger-wagging.

50:52.917 --> 50:57.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there's this sense of
connection, a sense
of people wanting to join
together, a sense

50:57.154 --> 51:03.794 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of -- I think a sense of
community and a feeling
that, even though these are
political times,

51:03.827 --> 51:05.329 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this is not an us-and-them
situation.

51:05.362 --> 51:09.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: That includes
artists looking
hard at their own communities.

51:09.466 --> 51:15.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Deana Lawson's photo series
evokes a family
album, presenting an intimate
look into lives

51:15.039 --> 51:16.774 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in her hometown.

51:16.807 --> 51:19.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DEANA LAWSON, Artist: The reason
why I chose
photography is because of that
immediacy,

51:19.677 --> 51:21.445 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that sort of documentary feel.

51:21.478 --> 51:26.350 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's oftentimes very staged,
so it's that
dialogue that I'm interested in.

51:26.383 --> 51:29.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I do want to pay a certain honor
to them,
at least in a sense.

51:29.486 --> 51:31.655 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: People who are
not the subject
of art so much.

51:31.689 --> 51:34.291 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
DEANA LAWSON: Right, and
traditional art,
correct.

51:34.325 --> 51:39.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I'm from a working-class
family in Rochester,
so a lot of the subjects I'm
gravitated to

51:39.463 --> 51:41.131 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
are from working-class
environments.

51:41.165 --> 51:45.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Henry Taylor's
large- scale
figurative paintings address the
mundane,

51:45.769 --> 51:51.508 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a summer barbecue, and conflict,
black men's
encounters with police.

51:51.542 --> 51:57.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a lot of painting here,
in fact, much
of it by first-time participants
and women.

51:57.414 --> 52:03.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Aliza Nisenbaum spends hours
with her subjects
to depict scenes of everyday
life, but also

52:03.053 --> 52:05.155 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the immigrant experience.

52:05.189 --> 52:09.226 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Dana Schutz uses a collage
effect of color
and energy.

52:09.259 --> 52:11.562 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then there's 87 year Jo
Baer.

52:11.595 --> 52:14.465 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
You're sort of the elder
stateswoman here,
right?

52:14.498 --> 52:15.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JO BAER, Artist: Apparently.

52:15.799 --> 52:16.767 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

52:16.800 --> 52:18.469 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Well, who knew?

52:18.502 --> 52:21.905 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Baer is a
renowned veteran
in the art world, still very
much at it with

52:21.939 --> 52:27.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a new series of paintings, and
returning to
the biennial after several
decades.

52:27.277 --> 52:31.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's a number of younger,
especially women
painters in this show.

52:31.648 --> 52:32.616 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
JO BAER: Yes.

52:32.649 --> 52:33.617 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

52:33.650 --> 52:34.618 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: How does that
make you feel?

52:34.651 --> 52:36.186 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JO BAER: Marvelous.

52:36.220 --> 52:37.688 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, look how well these
paintings go with
all these younger paintings.

52:37.721 --> 52:39.790 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Look at this installation.

52:39.823 --> 52:41.191 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It is so mind-boggling.

52:41.225 --> 52:49.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is such a joy to see that
what I'm doing
is what they're doing.

52:49.199 --> 52:54.772 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Taken altogether,
curators
Lew and Locks present artists
eager to engage

52:54.805 --> 52:58.008 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in ways not always associated
with contemporary
art.

52:58.042 --> 52:59.877 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
CHRISTOPHER Y.

52:59.910 --> 53:03.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LEW: Even in artists that are
riffing on pop
culture or using more
appropriated imagery,

53:03.547 --> 53:09.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they're doing it in a way that
comes out of
a certain sense of emotion and
kind of sincere

53:09.086 --> 53:11.522 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
interest, and not just for a
kind of ironic
pastiche.

53:11.555 --> 53:15.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIA LOCKS: Actually, we were
surprised, in
some ways, that, as the show
came together,

53:15.893 --> 53:20.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there are a number of works that
do point
to or suggest maybe more healing
possibilities

53:20.798 --> 53:26.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of art, or this kind of sense of
kind of reparative
practices, which are -- maybe
that's symptomatic.

53:26.370 --> 53:27.871 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Maybe that's what we need of art
right now.

53:27.905 --> 53:31.842 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The biennial
exhibition is
up through June 11.

